      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for any previous misunderstanding. Urban streetwear is characterized by its bold and expressive visual language, often reflecting the vibrancy and diversity of the communities it originates from. Key visual elements include:\n\n1. Color Palette: Bold, saturated colors are prevalent, with a mix of primary colors (red, blue, yellow) and neon hues that stand out and are reminiscent of graffiti art and street art.\n2. Silhouettes: Loose-fitting, oversized silhouettes are common, often paired with baggy cargo pants or wide-legged pants. Jackets and hoodies with oversized fits, often featuring unique cuts or asymmetrical designs, are also popular.\n3. Motifs: Graffiti-inspired lettering, throwback logos, and iconic symbols from hip-hop culture are frequently used. These can include stylized text, emblematic imagery like the \"X\" or \"5,\" and references to famous street artists or hip-hop icons.\n4. Materials: Durable fabrics like cotton, denim, and leather, as well as innovative materials like mesh and reflective fabrics, are used to create pieces that are both comfortable and functional.\n5. Prints and Graphics: Bold graphics, abstract designs, and urban landscapes are commonly incorporated into the fabric, often through screen printing or digital printing techniques.",
      "source": "target",
